Homework 5¶

Task 1¶

We are given function $f(x_1, x_2) = (x_1 + x_2)^2 = x_1^2 + 2 x_1 x_2 + x_2^2$ and two random variables $X_{1,2}$. Let's calculate PD profile for variable $X_1$: $$ g_1^{PD}(z) = E_{X_2}(z^2 + 2zx_2 + x_2^2) = z^2 + 2zE_{X_2}(X_2) + E_{X_2}(X_2^2) $$ We now that $E_{X_2}(X_2) = \frac{-1 + 1}{2} = 0$ and $E_{X_2}(X_2^2) = \int_{-1}^1 x^2 \frac{1}{2} dx = \frac{x^3}{6} |_{-1}^1 = \frac{2}{6} = \frac{1}{3}$ So finally we have that $$ g_1^{PD}(z) = z^2 + \frac{1}{3} $$

from IPython.display import Image

Ceteris Paribus profiles of labels 0 and 1 for XGBoost¶

Like in previous homeworks, I used the wines dataset, which is characterized by a significant disproportion in its label distribution. In the first experiments I was using XGBoost as a model (0. homework) and dalex library to plot Ceteris Paribus (2. homework) or Partial Dependence Profiles To illustrate the model's performance and its interpretability, I selected three samples for analysis (1. homework):

  • id 2416 - label 0 - correctly predicted by the model
  • id 1541 - label 1 - incorrectly predicted by the model
  • id 1739 - label 1 - correctly predicted by the model
In [14]:
Image("imgs/labels_cp.png")
Out[14]:

Even in this single plot we can get a lot of insight. For example in the plots of citric_acid, chlorides, alcohol, free_sulfur_dioxide (or others but not as clear) we can see that samples with label 1 (not necessarily correctly predicted by the model) behaves pretty much the same. However, the one predicted wrongly seems to be less influenced by these features. The strangest thing occurs in the plot of volatile_acidity (3. homework), here sample 2 Ceteris Paribus closer remarks the plot from label 0 then another label 1 but correctly predicted. For sample 1739 the plot increase earlier more rapid than for other two samples. Last but not least we can see that in general Ceteris Paribus values for label 0 are far less sensitive to the majority of variables. Maybe model focuses too much on volatile_acidity?

In [15]:
Image("imgs/many_cp.png")

This plot represents Ceteris Paribus plots for randomly chosen 50 samples. We can see that majority of lines resembles label 0 - makes sense due to class imbalance. By looking at volatile_acidity we can make a guess that we've found one correctly predicted label 1 and few false negatives. By choosing 50 samples we can image how will the Partial Dependence Profiles plot look like - average of all lines.

PDP of XGBoost¶

In [16]:
Image("imgs/pdp.png")
Out[16]:

That is Partial Dependence Profiles plot of test dataset (4. homework). Most of lines are close to 0 - less sensitivity of label 0 which is more common. Also once again volatile_acidity resembles characteristic of label 0. Interesting one is free_sulfur_dioxide. For our label 0 candidate it was completely flat. But in PDP we can see huge increase, almost vertical line on the left which was also present in the samples with label 1. Maybe even small portion of huge values moved average so drastically.

Comparison of PDP of XGBoost and Random Forest Classifier¶

In [17]:
Image("imgs/pdp_comp.png")
Out[17]:

In the final experiment I compared pdp plots of previously analysed XGBoost and Random Forest Classifier (5. homework). Let's see if we can spot some differences among the models. At first, we can see that Random Forest Classifier is much more sensitive - in all plots the green line is above the gray. In the plot with total_sulfur_dioxide of XGBoost nothing happens, however for RFC it has both tails high with valley in the middle. Maybe we can find some similarity in the volatile_acidity, a gentle slope is followed by significant increase at around 0.6.
